Okay, I will analyze the provided information to address the error and implement the requested design changes.

Based on the error message "Element type is invalid: expected a string (for built-in components) or a class/function (for composite components) but got: undefined," and the recent changes, the issue was related to an incorrect import of `WidgetContext`. It seems you were importing `WidgetContext` instead of `WidgetProvider`. This has already been corrected in the provided code snippet:

```typescript
// app/_layout.tsx
import { WidgetProvider } from '../contexts/WidgetContext'; // Corrected import

function RootLayout() {
  return (
    <AuthProvider>
      <SettingsProvider>
        <WidgetProvider>
          <Stack>
            {/* ... */}
          </Stack>
        </WidgetProvider>
      </SettingsProvider>
    </AuthProvider>
  );
}
```

If you've made this correction and are still encountering the error, ensure that:

1.  `WidgetProvider` is correctly exported from `../contexts/WidgetContext.tsx` (or .js).
2.  There are no other components with similar import/export issues.
3.  All component names are correctly spelled and referenced.

After reviewing the code, I've identified a potential issue in `contexts/WidgetContext.tsx`. The code directly imports and uses `ExtensionStorage` from `@bacons/apple-targets` without checking the platform. This can lead to errors on non-iOS platforms.

Here's the problematic code:

```typescript
import * as React from "react";
import { createContext, useCallback, useContext } from "react";
import { ExtensionStorage } from "@bacons/apple-targets";

// Initialize storage with your group ID
const storage = new ExtensionStorage(
  "group.com.<user_name>.<app_name>"
);

type WidgetContextType = {
  refreshWidget: () => void;
};

const WidgetContext = createContext<WidgetContextType | null>(null);

export function WidgetProvider({ children }: { children: React.ReactNode }) {
  // Update widget state whenever what we want to show changes
  React.useEffect(() => {
    // set widget_state to null if we want to reset the widget
    // storage.set("widget_state", null);

    // Refresh widget
    ExtensionStorage.reloadWidget();
  }, []);

  const refreshWidget = useCallback(() => {
    ExtensionStorage.reloadWidget();
  }, []);

  return (
    <WidgetContext.Provider value={{ refreshWidget }}>
      {children}
    </WidgetContext.Provider>
  );
}

export const useWidget = () => {
  const context = useContext(WidgetContext);
  if (!context) {
    throw new Error("useWidget must be used within a WidgetProvider");
  }
  return context;
};
```

To fix this, I will modify `contexts/WidgetContext.tsx` to conditionally import and use `ExtensionStorage` only on iOS. This will prevent errors on other platforms.

Here's the proposed change:

```typescript
import * as React from "react";
import { createContext, useCallback, useContext, useEffect } from "react";
import { Platform } from 'react-native';

let ExtensionStorage: any = null;

type WidgetContextType = {
  refreshWidget: () => void;
};

const WidgetContext = createContext<WidgetContextType | null>(null);

export function WidgetProvider({ children }: { children: React.ReactNode }) {
  const [isExtensionStorageLoaded, setIsExtensionStorageLoaded] = React.useState(false);

  useEffect(() => {
    if (Platform.OS === 'ios') {
      import('@bacons/apple-targets').then(module => {
        ExtensionStorage = module.ExtensionStorage;
        setIsExtensionStorageLoaded(true);
      });
    } else {
      setIsExtensionStorageLoaded(true); // Consider it loaded on other platforms
    }
  }, []);


  const refreshWidget = useCallback(() => {
    if (Platform.OS === 'ios' && ExtensionStorage) {
      ExtensionStorage.reloadWidget();
    }
  }, []);

  return (
    <WidgetContext.Provider value={{ refreshWidget }}>
      {children}
    </WidgetContext.Provider>
  );
}

export const useWidget = () => {
  const context = useContext(WidgetContext);
  if (!context) {
    throw new Error("useWidget must be used within a WidgetProvider");
  }
  return context;
};
```

This change ensures that `ExtensionStorage` is only imported and used on iOS platforms, preventing the "Element type is invalid" error on other platforms.

